   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_196289_1823_12_02_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"/>Edgeworths Town
                  <date when="1823-12-02">Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 2<hi rend="superscript">nd</hi>, 1823.</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                     Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JacoW1">Sir</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Can you do me the favor<lb/>
               to receive and <del>forward</del>
               <lb/>
               obtain Government franks<lb/>
               to forward for me two or<lb/>
               three packets containing<lb/>
               about 20 pages each of <choice>
                  <orig>M<hi rend="superscript">s.</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>manuscripts</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               which I wish to send to two<lb/>
               or three friends in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK"/>England<lb/>
               to be corrected for me -<lb/>
               The <choice>
                  <orig>M<hi rend="superscript">s.</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>manuscript</reg>
               </choice> is a sequel to <title ref="./Workography.xml#Harry1">Harry<lb/> and Lucy</title>
               - the first packet<lb/>
               I should want to send <choice>
                  <orig>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>would</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               be to M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StruW1"> William Strutt</persName> of<lb/>
               S<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi> Helens near <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Derby_ENK"/>Derby to correct<lb/>
               the account of a cotton <choice>
                  <orig>manu-<lb/>
                  factory</orig>
                  <reg>manufactory</reg>
               </choice> - This I should wish<lb/>
               him to return to you &amp; by<lb/>
               your means to have returned<lb/>
               to me - The other packets<lb/>
               would<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_196289_1823_12_02_page02.jpg"/>
               be addressed to persons in<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK"/>London &amp; would not therefore<lb/>
               require any franks to forward<lb/>
               them - but they would require<lb/>
               <add>you<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </add>
               <lb/>
               franks to send them back to<lb/>
               me - Can you manage this for<lb/>
               me - I know it is a great favor<lb/>
               in the present strictness of<lb/>
               Commissioners.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I hope your family my<lb/>
               dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JacoW1">Sir</persName> continue in health<lb/>
               and happiness - We are in<lb/>
               great anxiety from the state<lb/>
               of my sister <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lucy</persName>- in whose side<lb/>
               an abscess is forming - The<lb/>
               crisis must be most perilous<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I wish I could by telling you<lb/>
               anything interesting or <choice>
                  <orig>entertain<lb/>
                  ing</orig>
                  <reg>entertaining</reg>
               </choice> earn one of your valuable<lb/>
               letters but alas I have nothing<lb/>
               to tell you but that I am with<lb/>
               affectionate remembrances to all<lb/>
               of your family I have the pleasure to be<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>

               Your obliged<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>
                  <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_196289_1823_12_02_page03.jpg"/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LondF1">Lady Londonderry</persName> has<lb/>
                  astonished all the good<lb/>
                  people of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE"/>Dublin - natives<lb/>
                  &amp; foreigners by riding thro'<lb/>
                  the streets in full <choice>
                     <orig>regimen-<lb/>
                     tal</orig>
                     <reg>regimental</reg>
                  </choice> uniform, with a sword<lb/>
                  by her side richly emblazoned<lb/>
                  with jewels, and on <choice>
                     <orig>Bona-<lb/>
                     partes</orig>
                     <reg>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BonaN1">Bonaparte</persName>s</reg>
                  </choice> own white charger<lb/>
                  reviewing her <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VaneC1">husbands</persName>
                  <lb/>
                  regiment in the park along<lb/>
                  with his <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VaneC1">Lordship</persName>
                  <lb/>
                  The force of female folly<lb/>
                  cannot no further go! w<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                  <lb/>
                  The officers of the reg<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi>
                  <add>10th</add>
                  <lb/>
               gave her a ball in the<lb/>
               evening and she danced<lb/>
                  under the happy weight<lb/>
               one hundred and eight<lb/>
               thousand pounds! -<lb/>
               Interest on this<lb/>
               calculate!<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_196289_1823_12_02_page04.jpg"/>
               Will you have the goodness<lb/>
               to have the enclosed put<lb/>
               into the 2<hi rend="superscript">d.</hi> post -- M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StriX2">Strickland</persName>
                  <lb/>
               to whom it is addressed is a<lb/>
               man you would like - He<lb/>
               has been in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE"/>Ireland 4 years<lb/>
               managing the great estates of<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DillH1">Lord Dillon</persName> -<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <note>Dec<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> 2 1823<lb/>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">M Edgeworth</persName>
                  </note>
                  <lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JacoW1">W. Jacob Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>
                     </persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
